x^2+9&=10 \quad \text{if } x<-5,\\
3x-8&=10 \quad \text{if } x\ge-5.
\end{align*}
Step 3: 
\begin{align*}
x^2+9&=10 \quad \text{if } x<-5 \Rightarrow x^2=1 \Rightarrow x=-1,\\
3x-8&=10 \quad \text{if } x\ge-5 \Rightarrow 3x=18 \Rightarrow x=6.
\end{align*}
Since $x=-1$ is not in the domain of the function for $x\ge-5$ and $x=6$ is not in the domain of the function for $x<-5$, then we must test both values in the other domain to determine which are valid solutions.
Step 4:
\begin{align*}
x^2+9&=10 \quad \text{if } x<-5 \Rightarrow x^2=1 \Rightarrow x=-1,\\
3x-8&=10 \quad \text{if } x\ge-5 \Rightarrow 3x=18 \Rightarrow x=6.
\end{align*}
Test $x=-1$ in the function for $x\ge-5$.
\begin{align*}
f(-1)&=3(-1)-8=-11\neq10.
\end{align*}
Test $x=6$ in the function for $x<-5$.
\begin{align*}
f(6)&=6^2+9=39\neq10.
\end{align*}
Since neither $x=-1$ nor $x=6$ works, then there are no solutions to $f(x)=10$ and the sum of all possible values of $x$ is $-1+6=5$.
Final Answer: The final answer is 5.

